explanation:
To determine whether OS_ForEachObjectOfType is dead code (i.e., its removal would not affect program behaviour) you must know both whether it is ever reached/used and whether its body has observable side effects. The listed symbols are the minimal additional items needed for that analysis:

- OS_DeleteAllObjects: Direct caller of OS_ForEachObjectOfType; required to check whether any runtime paths call the target.
- OS_ForEachObject: Direct caller of OS_ForEachObjectOfType; needed to trace other call sites that may reach the target.
- OS_API_Teardown: Caller of OS_DeleteAllObjects (an entry/shutdown path); needed to decide whether the caller chain is reachable in typical execution (affects reachability/necessity).

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit: Callee inside the target that initializes iteration; its success/failure and side effects determine whether the function does observable work.
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext: Controls whether the loop body executes; needed to know if the loop ever iterates (if it never yields entries the body may be no-op).
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry: Performs per-entry processing; if it has side effects then OS_ForEachObjectOfType is not dead; must be inspected.
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy: Cleanup called by the target; may have observable effects/resources to be considered.

- OS_ForEachFilterCreator: Predicate callback passed to IteratorInit; if it has side effects or is used elsewhere, that affects whether removing the target changes behaviour.
- OS_ForEachDoCallback: The user callback passed to ProcessEntry; crucial to know if it performs observable actions (removal would change behavior).

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit and OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Used by the iterator init/destroy paths (per static graph); they may alter global/object state (transactions) and thus are relevant to whether the target contributes observable effects.
- OS_GetMaxForObjectType and OS_GetBaseForObjectType: Used by iterator init to determine iteration range; needed to see whether any objects could ever be iterated (impacting whether the loop is ever active).

- OS_ObjectIdFromToken, OS_Lock_Global, OS_Unlock_Global: Called (via ProcessEntry) while processing entries; locking/unlocking or token translation are observable runtime operations — their presence means the target may affect concurrency/state.

- UT_ExecuteBasicHandler and UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData: The unit-test / stub dispatcher symbols that appear in the static graph as callers/related instrumentation; include them to check whether test harness paths or stubbed handlers can reach the target (affects perceived dead-ness in test builds).

Together these symbols let the next analyst (or tool) determine: (a) whether any live call paths reach OS_ForEachObjectOfType, (b) whether its internal calls/callbacks have observable side effects, and (c) whether removing it would change program behaviour (i.e., not be dead code).
